00:08:29.628 --> 00:08:31.105
elements.
Now what's really,

00:08:31.105 --> 00:08:32.940
what makes this a sequential
move game?

00:08:32.940 --> 00:08:36.528
Let's be careful about this.
What makes it a sequential move

00:08:36.528 --> 00:08:41.077
game is not simply that Player I
moved first and Player II moved

00:08:41.077 --> 00:08:43.532
second,
although that's true,

00:08:43.532 --> 00:08:47.740
what really made this a
sequential move game is that

00:08:47.740 --> 00:08:52.855
Player II knew what Player I had
done before he got to make his

00:08:52.855 --> 00:08:55.855
move.
It isn't the timing per se that

00:08:55.855 --> 00:08:59.995
matters, it's going to turn out
it's the fact that Player II

00:08:59.995 --> 00:09:04.415
could observe Player I's choice
before having to make his or her

00:09:04.415 --> 00:09:08.352
choice that matters.
Notice, just while we're on the

00:09:08.352 --> 00:09:12.646
subject, more than that Player I
knew this was going to be the

00:09:12.646 --> 00:09:16.820
case.
So let's just get that down.

00:09:16.820 --> 00:09:27.692
So in this game Player II knows
Player I's choice before she

00:09:27.692 --> 00:09:38.750
chooses--she being Player II,
let's say before II chooses.

00:09:38.750 --> 00:09:45.694
Second, Player I knows that
this will be the case,

00:09:45.694 --> 00:09:53.913
and the way we dramatized this
just now is Player I put the

00:09:53.913 --> 00:09:58.524
money in the hat,
the hat was transported across

00:09:58.524 --> 00:10:01.848
the classroom with people very
honestly not stealing the money

00:10:01.848 --> 00:10:04.431
to Player II,
Player II could look in the

00:10:04.431 --> 00:10:07.093
hat, could see how much money
was in there,

00:10:07.093 --> 00:10:10.200
before Steven or Nate had to
make that choice.

00:10:10.200 --> 00:10:14.619
Is that right?
So how do we go about analyzing

00:10:14.619 --> 00:10:17.379
games that have this sequential
structure?

